III. THE BRNSTEDEVANSPOLANYI RELATION
Consider first dissociation and adsorption of N2 on the
most closely packed surface of the different metals. We find
an essentially linear relationship like that in the Brnsted
EvansPolanyi relation over a broad range of adsorption
energies and barriers (Fig. 1). The slope we find in the acti-
vation barrier vs adsorption energy plot is 0.9.
The calculations show why the BrnstedEvansPolanyi
relation is obeyed in this case. The transition state we find
for N2 dissociation on all the surfaces is so stretched (see
inset in Fig. 1) that the direct interaction between two
N atoms is quite weakthe transition state is final state-
like.
